<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Sponsored in part by Elsevier, publisher of
International Journal of Infectious Disease
<http://thelancet.url123.com/a58n7>
[1]
Date: 12 Nov 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Times of India [edited]
<http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/1292942.cms>

Confusion over mystery disease
-----------------------------------
Villagers from Saharanpur, Muzaffarnagar, Baghpat, Bijnor, Ghaziabad
and Meerut in western Uttar Pradesh call it "the annual winter
fever." It has claimed about 326 lives since 2002.
Yet, the official strategy to check this "mystery virus in the west"
is to patiently wait until the temperature drops below 16 C and the
virus dies a natural death, since no one has a clue about its
identity.
"It is much easier to fight Japanese encephalitis in Purvanchal. At
least we can take necessary preventive measures. But here we are
absolutely at sea. After all, one can only cure a disease one
identifies," a hapless senior health official told TOI. Close to 100
children have succumbed to the disease in Saharanpur during the last
month-and-a-half [October-November 2005].
The confusion persists despite annual visits by public health
experts, epidemiologists, microbiologists and entomologists from the
National Institute of Virology (NIV) Pune, the National Institute of
Communicable Diseases (NICD) and the National Vector Born Disease
Control Programme to collect samples.
These are routinely followed by a visit from a high-powered team from
the state government. The achievements so far are contradictory
reports by NIV and NICD in 2003 and a spate of suspensions, including
that of CMO Saharanpur at the same time.
According to records, findings so far have varied from eco virus,
herpes simplex virus and JE in 2002-03 to a "cocktail virus" with
traces of JE, eco virus, malaria, and virus encephalitis.
Causing greater worry to health experts is expansion of the endemic
pocket. The virus, confined to Saharanpur for the last 10 years, has
now spread its tentacles into Ghaziabad and Baghpat too.
In fact, patients from Baghpat chose to go to Delhi, 24 km away, for
treatment. None visited the Baghpat primary health center last year
[2004], sources said.
They even hinted at the possibility of a similar strain traveling as
far as Karnal, where deaths of children, especially girls, were
reported recently.
What vexes experts is the government's insistence in sending samples
to Delhi or Pune when Sanjay Gandhi Postgraduate Institute (SGPGI),
Lucknow has all facilities for viral isolation.
Dr. TN Dhole, professor in microbiology at SGPGI admitted that the
institute had not received a single sample for examination in the
last 10 years. This, when NICD does not have a self-culture system,
he said.
[Byline: Manjari Mishra]
--
